04855nam a22006735i 9780292798502DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212003txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927985027 a10.7560/7526342doi  a(DE-B1597)588021  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aD810.C88bM43 2002eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a940.54/032211 aMeadows, William C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Comanche Code Talkers of World War II /cWilliam C. Meadows. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on the Comanche Sound System -- t1. The Origins of Native American Code Talking -- t2. Native American Servicemen and Code Talkers in World War II -- t3. “Get him back on that scale and weigh him again!” -- t4. “Utekwapa naka: I hear what you say.” -- t5. Fighting Po’sataiboo’: Crazy White Man -- t6. “Numurekwa’etuu: Comanche Speakers!” -- tA. Members of Company E, 142d Infantry, Thirty-sixth Division, World War I -- tB. World War I Choctaw Code Talkers -- tC. Organization of the Fourth Infantry Division, 1941–1945 -- tD. Combat Narrative of the Fourth Infantry Division -- tE. Fourth Infantry Division Campaign (June 6, 1944, to May 8, 1945) -- tF. Fourth Signal Company Activities, 1940 –1945 -- tG. Glossary of Comanche Code Terms -- tH. Known Native American Code Talkers of World Wars I and II (Tribes, Group Size, Form of Code Talking, and Military Units) -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong the allied troops that came ashore in Normandy on D-Day, June 6, 1944, were thirteen Comanches in the 4th Infantry Division, 4th Signal Company. Under German fire they laid communications lines and began sending messages in a form never before heard in Europe—coded Comanche. For the rest of World War II, the Comanche Code Talkers played a vital role in transmitting orders and messages in a code that was never broken by the Germans. This book tells the full story of the Comanche Code Talkers for the first time. Drawing on interviews with all surviving members of the unit, their original training officer, and fellow soldiers, as well as military records and news accounts, William C. Meadows follows the group from their recruitment and training to their active duty in World War II and on through their postwar lives up to the present. He also provides the first comparison of Native American code talking programs, comparing the Comanche Code Talkers with their better-known Navajo counterparts in the Pacific and with other Native Americans who used their languages, coded or not, for secret communication. Meadows sets this history in a larger discussion of the development of Native American code talking in World Wars I and II, identifying two distinct forms of Native American code talking, examining the attitudes of the American military toward Native American code talkers, and assessing the complex cultural factors that led Comanche and other Native Americans to serve their country in this way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aComanche Indians. 0aIndian code talkers. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCryptography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xParticipation, Indian. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zFrancezNormandy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCharney, Jean O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75263440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292798502423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292798502/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EB